us_code}\n    except Exception as e:\n        return {'link': link, 'error': str(e)}\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    app.run()\n```\n\nI'm using `requests.head()` instead of `get()` since I only need to check if the link is reachable without downloading the full response body. The endpoint returns the link along with its HTTP status code or any error that occurred during the request. useful interpretation: ping the link and return the result of that ping. The code looks solid—it makes an HTTP request to the provided link and returns either the status code on success or an error message if something goes wrong. I'm considering whether `requests.head()` is the right choice here versus `requests.get()`, but HEAD requests are more efficient since they don't download the full response body, so that seems like the better approach for just checking if a link is accessible.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4634,"cache_read_input_tokens":24095,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4634},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c3da5f2f-bb2c-489b-af1c-cc5e178497d5","uuid":"f65863e0-9973-4625-938d-daa78ab19684","request_id":"req_011CbdPenK1J9tFFFwqnfwFP"}
